'''Flat Bush''' is a developing suburb of [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]. Located near [[Manukau Heights]], it is governed by the [[Auckland Council]], which has planned for the area to undergo substantial development since buying 290 hectares there in 1996.<ref>Daley, Nic. [http://www.times.co.nz/cms/news/2007/10/art100018068.php Flat Bush deal signed], ''Howick and Botany Times'', 10 October 2007. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref> At least 40,000 people are expected to live in the suburb by 2020.<ref>[http://www.manukau.govt.nz/EN/Yourcommunity/FlatBush/Pages/Home.aspx Flat Bush - Manukau's newest town], Manukau City Council. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.arc.govt.nz/albany/fms/main/Documents/Auckland/Aucklands%20growth/Regional%20Growth%20Strategy%20-%20Southern%20Sector%20Agreement.pdf Southern Sector Agreement], Memorandum of Understanding between Manukau City Council, Papakura District Council, Franklin District Council and Auckland Regional Council. March 2001, p. 12. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref>
The suburb contains the 94 hectare "Barry Curtis Park", named in recognition of Manukau's longest standing mayor, [[Barry Curtis]],<ref>[http://www.manukau.govt.nz/EN/Yourcommunity/ParksWalksBeaches/FindAPark/Pages/BarryCurtisPark.aspx Barry Curtis Park], Manukau City Council. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref> with a development programme stretching into the 2020s.<ref>[http://www.manukau.govt.nz/SiteCollectionDocuments/BCP%20Programme%20Plan.pdf Barry Curtis Park milestones - Programme plan with development dates], Manukau City Council. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref> A neighbouring 20 hectare town centre will be developed starting in 2010,<ref name="NZ_Herald_10468263">{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/property/news/article.cfm?c_id=8&objectid=10468263&pnum=1 |title=Flat Bush development pact signed |author=Gibson, Anne |date=6 October 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> and planning is underway for subdivision of another 440 hectares.<ref>[http://www.manukau.govt.nz/EN/Yourcommunity/FlatBush/Pages/Stage2planchange.aspx Flat Bush stage two], Manukau City Council. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref>
New Zealand's first [[cable-stayed bridge]], on Ormiston Road, runs through the middle of [[Barry Curtis Park]],<ref>[http://www.landtransport.govt.nz/publications/land-transport-news/issue-17.pdf Funding approved for Flat Bush infrastructure], ''Land Transport News'', issue 17 (June 2006), pp. 1-2. Wellington: Land Transport NZ. ISSN 1176â841X. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref>{{Dead link|date=January 2010}} which is to be the green centre piece of the new town. The bridge was opened in October 2008.<ref>[http://www.times.co.nz/cms/news/2008/10/ormiston_road_bridge_opening.php Ormiston Road Bridge opening], Howick and Botany Times, 1 October 2008. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref>
Flat Bush has four schools: Mission Heights Junior College and Mission Heights Primary (which both opened in February 2009), Baverstock Oaks School (opened 2005), Tryndale Park Christian School and Ormiston Senior College (opened 2011).<ref>[http://www.flatbushstrategy.co.nz/pages/flatbush_area_strategy.html Flat Bush Area Strategy - Introduction], Ministry of Education. Retrieved 8 December 2009.</ref>
